🖥️ Part 1 — Launch Two EC2 Instances:
        Step 1 — Navigate:
            Go to AWS Console → EC2
            Click "Launch Instance"
        Step 2 — Configure Instances:
        
        Table
        
        
        Setting	Value
        Name	First Instance
        Number of Instances	2(right side of the page)
        OS	Amazon Linux 2
        Instance Type	t2.micro (Free Tier)
        Key Pair	Proceed without Key Pair
        Security Group	Select Existing → launch-wizard-1
        Step 3 — Add User Data:
        
        Expand "Advanced Details"
        Scroll down to "User Data"
        Paste the following script:
        
        Copy
        bash
        #!/bin/bash
        # Use this for your user data (script from top to bottom)
        # Install httpd (Amazon Linux 2 version)
        yum update -y
        yum install -y httpd
        systemctl start httpd
        systemctl enable httpd
        echo "<h1>Hello World from $(hostname -f)</h1>" > /var/www/html/index.html
        Click "Launch Instance" ✅
        Step 4 — Rename Second Instance:
        
        Go to EC2 → Instances
        Find the second instance → Click the pencil icon on the name
        Rename it to Second Instance ✅
        💡 Both instances will display "Hello World from <hostname>" but with different hostnames — this proves ELB is routing to different instances

⚖️ Part 2 — Create Application Load Balancer:
Step 1 — Navigate:

In the left panel → Click "Load Balancers"
Click "Create Load Balancer"
Select "Application Load Balancer" → Click "Create"
Step 2 — Configure ALB:

Table


Setting	Value
Load Balancer Name	ELB-Demo-ALB
Scheme	Internet Facing
Availability Zones	Select ALL available AZs ✅
Step 3 — Create New Security Group:

Under Security Groups → Click "Create New Security Group"(opens new tab)
Configure:
Table


Setting	Value
Name	demo-sg-alb
Description	Security Group for ALB
Inbound Rule Type	HTTP
Port	80
Source	0.0.0.0/0 (Anywhere)
Click "Create Security Group" ✅
Go back to ALB page → Click Refresh on Security Groups
Remove the existing default security group
Selectdemo-sg-alb ✅
Step 4 — Create Target Group:

Under Listeners and Routing → Click "Create Target Group"(opens new tab)
Configure:
Table


Setting	Value
Target Type	Instances
Target Group Name	demo-tg-alb
Protocol	HTTP
Port	80
Click Next
Select both instances (First Instance and Second Instance)
Click "Include as Pending Below"
Click "Create Target Group" ✅
Go back to ALB page → Click Refresh on Target Group dropdown
Select demo-tg-alb ✅
Step 5 — Create Load Balancer:

Review all settings
Click "Create Load Balancer" ✅
⏳ Wait 2-5 minutes for state to change from Provisioning → Active

Step 6 — Test ALB:

Copy the DNS Name from ALB details
Open browser → Paste the DNS URL
Every time you refresh → Page loads from different instances:
Refresh 1 → Hello World from First Instance  (ip-172-31-x-x)
Refresh 2 → Hello World from Second Instance (ip-172-31-x-y)
Refresh 3 → Hello World from First Instance  (ip-172-31-x-x)
(Round Robin Load Balancing) ✅
🔐 Part 3 — Restrict Access via ALB Only:
⚠️ Problem: Currently both the ALB DNS and direct EC2 IP address can access the instances. We need to restrict access so that only ALB DNS can reach the instances.

Step 1 — Edit launch-wizard-1 Inbound Rules:

Go to EC2 → Security Groups
Select launch-wizard-1
Click "Inbound Rules" → "Edit Inbound Rules"
Delete the existing HTTP rule ❌
Step 2 — Add New HTTP Rule:

Click "Add Rule"
Configure:
Table


Setting	Value
Type	HTTP
Port	80
Source	Custom → Search demo-sg-alb → Select it
Click "Save Rules" ✅
Step 3 — Verify:

Direct EC2 IP → http://13.127.x.x      ❌ Not accessible
ALB DNS       → http://ELB-Demo-ALB... ✅ Accessible

Traffic flow now:
Users → ALB (demo-sg-alb) → launch-wizard-1 → EC2 Instances
💡 Now instances are only accessible through the ALB DNS — direct IP access is blocked ✅

📋 Part 4 — Add Custom HTTP Rule (Path-Based Routing):
💡 What is this? ALB can route traffic to different responses based on the URL path. Here we create a rule that returns a custom error for /error path.

Step 1 — Navigate to ALB Rules:

Go to EC2 → Load Balancers
Select ELB-Demo-ALB
Click "Listeners and Rules" tab
Click "HTTP:80"
Step 2 — Add New Rule:

Click "Add Rule"
Configure Name/Tags:
Table


Setting	Value
Name	Demo Rule
Click Next
Step 3 — Add Condition:

Click "Add Condition"
Select Path
Enter path value:
/error
Click Next
Step 4 — Add Action:

Select "Return Fixed Response"
Configure:
Table


Setting	Value
Response Code	404
Content Type	text/plain
Response Body	Not found, custom error
Click Next
Step 5 — Set Priority:

Table


Setting	Value
Priority	1(Highest priority)
Click Next → "Save" ✅
Step 6 — Test the Rule:

Open browser → Paste ALB DNS + /error:
http://ELB-Demo-ALB-xxxx.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com/error
Result:
Not found, custom error ✅
